attributeDefinition: Datapoint identifier
Common name of the seabird predator
Scientific name of the seabird (predator) species
Year or midpoint of range of years (rounded up to the nearest year) during which diet samples were taken
Year or start of range of years during which diet samples were taken
Year or end of range of years during which diet samples were taken
Whether samples were taken over a range of multiple years

Location where diet samples were taken, typically a breeding colony, as given in the reporting study. Where samples were taken over a wider region or where sampling was not distinguished between two or more locations, the midpoint between multiple locations was recorded
Location latitude (N)
Location longitude (E)
Whether diets were sampled during the Breeding season or the Non-breeding season
Predator age group. Whether the diet samples were collected from Adult or Chick. When age group could not be determined “adult & chick” was recorded.
The taxonomic term used in the original source
Prey taxonomic identity. Matched to the lowest possible taxonomic level.

Relative frequency of occurrence of a prey taxon across diet samples in a given study. For stomach content analyses, whenever possible this was expressed as a proportion of stomachs that had some content (i.e. empty stomachs were excluded). Frequency of occurrence of all prey taxa recorded in a particular study won’t necessarily sum to 1.
Relative numerical frequency of prey taxon among total number of recorded prey items. Numerical frequencies of all recorded prey taxa in a given study should sum to 1.
Relative biomass of prey taxon with respect to the total biomass/volume/energy recorded in a given study  (where biomass of all prey taxa was available)
Average prey size. Textual data as recorded in the data source which may contain standard deviation and inconsistent units
Number of samples from which relative frequencies have been calculated
Method used to assess diet
